Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["Solutions to Absolute Magnitude Practice", "Chapter",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.728383445304961*^9, 3.72838346773687*^9}, {
  3.728784799569207*^9, 
  3.728784810421509*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"db5d2ae6-3c10-4872-be7e-\
b3ab1ab3d5cd"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Practice Problem 1", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.728384391158197*^9, 
  3.7283843932826233`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"004ca53c-115c-4dba-8a66-\
131696234ea4"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Sirius has a magnitude of -1.46. Vega has a magnitude of 0.03.\n\n(a) Which \
is brighter?\n\nBigger magnitudes (2, 3, 4, etc) are dimmer.\n\nHere we have \
a negative magnitude. The more negative the brighter! So Sirius is brighter \
than Vega. In fact, Sirius is the brightest star in the sky and is easily \
visible right now.\n\n(b) The difference in magnitudes is?\n\n-1.46 - 0.03 = \
-1.49\n\n(c) If you use the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["2.5", 
    RowBox[{"difference", " ", "in", " ", "magnitudes"}]], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"5dd9e125-c0ce-44a6-858e-20b5726a3384"],
 " formula, that says that the Sirius is how much brighter than Vega?\n\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["2.5", "1.49"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "144694fd-e368-41e1-91af-6eae0254811b"],
 "=3.91\n\nNow, you might have done\n\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["2.5", 
    RowBox[{"-", "1.49"}]], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "3c44b7b9-7b94-409c-9e59-8336c824bcb5"],
 "\n\nAnd then your answer would be\n\n0.255\n\nThis is the reciprocal of \
3.91 and it\[CloseCurlyQuote]s not quite right. Sirius is not 0.255 times as \
bright as Vega. That would make it dimmer. So really you were looking for \n\n\
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   FractionBox["1", "0.255"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "d082a3f9-42bf-4e7f-abda-a980932adeb6"],
 "=3.91\n\nThis is just an area where you have to be careful and double-check \
your answers for sensibility. If someone says \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]the \
Tesla is 1/3 the price of the Prius\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] you say \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]go check your math.\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] Sure \
enough, they\[CloseCurlyQuote]ll come back at you and say, \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]the Prius is 1/3 the price of the Tesla,\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] or alternatively, \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]the Tesla \
is 3 times the price of the Prius.\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]\n\n(d) If you use \
the actual ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["100", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"difference", " ", "in", " ", "magnitudes"}], ")"}], "/", 
     "5"}]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "70866c5c-bc2b-49f3-a823-96a633653dd4"],
 " formula what do you get?"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.728384410429407*^9, 3.728384762352045*^9}, {
  3.728384801086747*^9, 3.728384844274946*^9}, {3.7283865194748163`*^9, 
  3.7283865208557253`*^9}, {3.728783338718165*^9, 3.72878344636525*^9}, {
  3.7287834816948423`*^9, 
  3.7287836916305304`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9d770498-7142-473e-81be-\
5cd1eea78de8"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 SuperscriptBox["100", 
  RowBox[{"1.49", "/", "5"}]]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7287836985710897`*^9, 
  3.728783714038179*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e206af38-48a7-49e2-bad2-\
037cded4d707"],

Cell[BoxData["3.944573020752784`"], "Output",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.728783714968071*^9},ExpressionUUID->"70cc5f36-0b07-49bf-8795-\
8acf697f13a0"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell["\<\
So, that\[CloseCurlyQuote]s pretty close to 3.91. If you didn\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]t get something close make sure you divided by 5 before \
exponentiating.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7287837354148073`*^9, 
  3.7287837560121937`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9bdb388e-5234-4de8-9419-\
187c8ac9087e"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Practice Problem 2", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.728384391158197*^9, 3.7283843932826233`*^9}, {
  3.728384672522908*^9, 
  3.7283846726998777`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a8537fbd-a767-4a13-830a-\
b56d81358d50"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The Full Moon has magnitude of about -12.6. The Sun has magnitude of about \
-26.7.\n\n(a) The difference in magnitudes is?\n\n-12.6 - (-26.7)=14.1\n\n(b) \
If you use the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["2.5", 
    RowBox[{"difference", " ", "in", " ", "magnitudes"}]], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"6dedfdbb-6d89-43c1-8a05-db67a41c0d3c"],
 " formula, that says that the Sun is how much brighter than the Moon?\n\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["2.5", "14.1"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "27f50f56-64d2-4dc8-97a5-da09c40e65a3"],
 "=408276\n\n(c) That\[CloseCurlyQuote]s a lot of magnitude difference. The \
errors pile up like compounded interest. If you use the actual ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["100", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"difference", " ", "in", " ", "magnitudes"}], ")"}], "/", 
     "5"}]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "e749ccd7-7c6c-4270-afce-182ebc536adb"],
 " what do you get?"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.728384410429407*^9, 3.728384662834321*^9}, {
  3.728384868925468*^9, 3.7283848827501*^9}, {3.72838495766807*^9, 
  3.728384958037331*^9}, {3.728386558847187*^9, 3.728386560682433*^9}, {
  3.728783762031423*^9, 
  3.7287838263706427`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"795fdd01-a451-4c6b-874b-\
d52215848985"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

