Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Practice Problem 4", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.728384391158197*^9, 3.7283843932826233`*^9}, {
  3.728385391859515*^9, 3.7283853919717407`*^9}, {3.728385932943203*^9, 
  3.728385932997663*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6cc16e0e-d015-4938-bf06-\
baafff026351"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Now this is going to get harder because you can\[CloseCurlyQuote]t do this \
problem without combining all of the previous concepts and definitions. If \
you get stuck, you need to take advantage of my office hours (please!). My \
office hours are easy to find by clicking on the link in the bottom of every \
one of my email messages.\n\nStar 1 and Star 2 have the same absolute \
magnitude. Star 1 is 5 parsecs away. Star 2 appears dimmer. To be precise, \
Star 1\[CloseCurlyQuote]s apparent magnitude is 2.0 and Star 2\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s apparent magnitude is 7.0.\n\nHow far away is Star 2?\n\n\
7.0-2.0 is 5.0, so we have a nice round 5 magnitudes of difference.\n\nThe \
brightness ratio is\n\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"100", "^", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"5", "/", "5"}], ")"}]}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     SuperscriptBox["100", "1"], "=", "100."}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "d43c15fe-ee78-46bd-9aa6-19f3b3fcc159"],
 "\n\nSo Star 2 appears 1/100 as bright as Star 1. Or if you prefer, Star 1 \
appears 100 times as bright as Star 2.\n\nIf they are truly the same \
brightness what could cause that!?!?\n\nWell, Star 2 must be a lot further \
away.\n\nIs it 100 times as far away? No! That would make it 1/10,000 as \
bright.\n\nIf it were 10 times as far away, that works, because ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["1", 
     SuperscriptBox["10", "2"]], "=", 
    FractionBox["1", "100"]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "be639e10-d198-42ce-8ecc-cf872f7bfcd7"],
 " and that is the brightness ratio we are looking for.\n\nIt is really handy \
for these kinds of problems to know some common squares.\n\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["2", "2"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "a0e4d2a8-d5df-4c3a-9acc-91b3f8421ed5"],
 "=4\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["3", "2"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "9e3801e4-b579-4e60-b945-65aba480c33b"],
 "=9\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["4", "2"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "3a09b69f-1a66-4017-81f9-74ec8b8f8761"],
 "=16\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["5", "2"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "0746b684-c71f-46a8-9185-d7ed465df682"],
 "=25\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["10", "2"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "99f6824a-b7cd-4db3-a77f-4346cab0b083"],
 "=100\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["100", "2"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "d083eaa4-94fa-4569-957b-15848de1bace"],
 "=10,000\n\nIf you know common squares and you can avoid punching them into \
your calculator, the right answers will jump out at you a lot faster. If you \
don\[CloseCurlyQuote]t know these, just patiently put them into your \
calculator. On a multiple choice problem that will be at most five things to \
punch in and some might be obviously wrong, so probably less."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.728385753798815*^9, 3.728385904301259*^9}, {
